All Implemented Interfaces:
ObjectLike
public class JsLocation
extends DOM.Location.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.Location class.

JsWindow.location property of the JsWindow object refers to a JsLocation object that represents the web address (the "location") of the document currently displayed in that window. The href property contains the complete URL of that document, and the other properties of the JsLocation object each describe a portion of that URL. These properties are much like the URL properties of the JsHTMLLinkElement object. When a JsLocation object is converted to a string, the value of the href property is returned.

While the JsHTMLLinkElement object represents a hyperlink in a document, the JsLocation object represents the URL, or location, currently displayed by the browser. However, the JsLocation object does more than that: it also controls the location displayed by the browser. If you assign a string containing a URL to the JsLocation object or to its href property, the web browser responds by loading the newly specified URL and displaying the document it refers to.

Instead of setting href to replace the current URL with a completely new one, you can modify just a portion of the current URL by assigning strings to the other properties of the JsLocation object. This creates a new URL with one new portion, which the browser loads and displays. For example, if you set the hash property of the JsLocation object, you can cause the browser to move to a named location within the current document. Similarly, if you set the search property, you can cause the browser to reload the current URL with a new query string appended.

In addition to its URL properties, the JsLocation object also defines two methods. The reload() method reloads the current document. The replace(Object) method loads a new document without creating a new history entry for it; the new document replaces the current one in the browser's history list.

reload

public void reload()

Reloads the current document from the cache or the server.

This method of the JsLocation object reloads the document that is currently displayed in the window of the JsLocation object. It uses the If-Modified-Since HTTP header to determine whether the document has changed on the web server. If the document has changed, the method reloads the document from the server, and if not, it reloads the document from the cache. This is the same action that occurs when the user clicks on the browser's Reload button.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

reload

public void reload(java.lang.Object force)

Reloads the current document from the cache or the server.

This method of the JsLocation object reloads the document that is currently displayed in the window of the JsLocation object. When called with no arguments or with the argument false, it uses the If-Modified-Since HTTP header to determine whether the document has changed on the web server. If the document has changed, the method reloads the document from the server, and if not, it reloads the document from the cache. This is the same action that occurs when the user clicks on the browser's Reload button.

When this method is called with the argument true, it always bypasses the cache and reloads the document from the server, regardless of the last-modified time of the document. This is the same action that occurs when the user Shift-clicks on the browser's Reload button.

Parameters:
force - An optional boolean argument that specifies whether the document should be reloaded even if the server reports that it has not been modified since it was last loaded. If this argument is false or undefined, the method reloads the full page only if it has changed since last loaded.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

replace

public void replace(java.lang.Object url)

Replaces the current document with a new one without generating a new entry in the browser's session history.

This method of the JsLocation object loads and displays a new document. Loading a document in this way is different from simply setting href in one important respect: this method does not generate a new entry in the JsHistory object. When you use this method, the new URL overwrites the current entry in the JsHistory object. After calling the method, the browser's Back button does not return you to the previous URL; it returns you to the URL before that one.

Parameters:
url - A string that specifies the URL of the new document that is to replace the current one.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
